13
00:00:50,960 --> 00:00:55,039
I'm Pat Walls, and this is Starter Story.

14
00:00:55,039 --> 00:00:56,960
All right, welcome Anya to the channel.

15
00:00:56,960 --> 00:00:59,920
Tell me about who you are, what you built, and what's your story.

16
00:00:59,920 --> 00:01:04,080
>> Hey, my name is Anya and I'm the founder of Rooted for Panic Attack and Anxiety Relief.

17
00:01:04,080 --> 00:01:11,040
Since launching in 2019, it's been downloaded over 4 million times and made over a million in revenue.

18
00:01:11,040 --> 00:01:12,560
>> I mean, wow, that's insane.

19
00:01:12,560 --> 00:01:15,280
4 million downloads on an app that you built.

20
00:01:15,280 --> 00:01:17,600
Can you tell me about how this all started?

21
00:01:17,600 --> 00:01:20,320
How you even came up with the idea to build something like this?

22
00:01:20,320 --> 00:01:25,600
Yeah, in my fourth year of university, I actually got a panic attack seemingly out of nowhere.

23
00:01:25,600 --> 00:01:28,960
I had no idea what they were before and I was far away from home.

24
00:01:28,960 --> 00:01:34,240
I had no family doctor and I really struggled to find the resources that I needed to get better.

25
00:01:34,240 --> 00:01:38,320
So, as I was looking through the app stores and looking online for something to help,

26
00:01:38,320 --> 00:01:40,799
I realized that there's nothing that really spoke to me.

27
00:01:40,799 --> 00:01:47,040
Things were really either clinical or there were hypnosis based apps and it just really wasn't what I was looking for.

28
00:01:47,040 --> 00:01:51,119
So that's why I figured I had something to launch here.

29
00:01:51,119 --> 00:01:54,960
>> I mean, I think what you did is awesome is that you actually had this personal problem,

30
00:01:54,960 --> 00:01:58,880
this very painful personal problem, and then you decided to build something.

31
00:01:58,880 --> 00:02:03,200
I guess my question is how'd you get the confidence to know that this was something worth building?

32
00:02:03,200 --> 00:02:07,200
How did you like validate that this could be something that could be big?

33
00:02:07,200 --> 00:02:07,520
>> Yeah.

34
00:02:07,520 --> 00:02:13,599
So my idea at the time was to download and try existing apps.

35
00:02:13,599 --> 00:02:24,080
And uh I noticed a common theme in the user reviews that there was this gap when it came to identifying what a panic attack is and also solutions for how to basically get through a panic attack in the moment.

36
00:02:24,080 --> 00:02:30,080
And I put together a really early version of Rooted, a prototype, an MVP type solution.

37
00:02:30,080 --> 00:02:34,400
And the first few hundred users said that even though there was still some lagging, some bugs,

38
00:02:34,400 --> 00:02:38,160
some incomplete parts, they really wanted me to keep going with it.

39
00:02:38,160 --> 00:02:39,760
And that was super encouraging.

40
00:02:39,760 --> 00:02:47,519
What would be your advice to someone who uh let's say they do have a personal problem like a painful problem like like mental health thing or or something like that.

41
00:02:47,519 --> 00:02:51,680
What would be your advice on how to like validate that this is something worth building?

42
00:02:51,680 --> 00:02:59,519
>> Yeah, I'd say if you are passionate about solving a problem then really launching with just an MVP to get that feedback out there.

43
00:02:59,519 --> 00:03:08,879
For me, I think I was just like obsessed with getting the idea out there and I really didn't then listen to the naysayers as much because I was like I need to prove this out myself.

44
00:03:08,879 --> 00:03:15,680
So, if you're confident that other people are experiencing your problem, it's worth just launching an MVP to see if what you've created will help them.

45
00:03:15,680 --> 00:03:15,920
>> Okay.

46
00:03:15,920 --> 00:03:17,200
Well, perfect segue on that.

47
00:03:17,200 --> 00:03:21,599
Let's talk about how you built that MVP, how you built the first version of that app.

48
00:03:21,599 --> 00:03:24,239
I understand that you don't have a technical background.

49
00:03:24,239 --> 00:03:26,080
You're not a programmer or coder.

50
00:03:26,080 --> 00:03:26,959
How did you do it?

51
00:03:26,959 --> 00:03:28,959
How did you build something worth using?

52
00:03:28,959 --> 00:03:38,319
>> I basically started taking what I thought would be helpful and I started drawing it out in a notebook and I was thinking about the way I wanted the information to be presented.

53
00:03:38,319 --> 00:03:41,360
what would be most helpful for me in that moment of a panic attack.

54
00:03:41,360 --> 00:03:46,080
How do I keep things super simple in the app when somebody's really overwhelmed as they're using it?

55
00:03:46,080 --> 00:03:56,080
And so I took these ideas and sketches from my notebooks and then I taught myself how to basically create them as wireframes in Photoshop and Illustrator.

56
00:03:56,080 --> 00:04:00,319
And then yeah, I went to an agency and I could not afford to work with the agency.

57
00:04:00,319 --> 00:04:02,400
So that certainly set me back timewise.

58
00:04:02,400 --> 00:04:11,680
But then at one point a student developer said that he would love to work with me and so that's how I was able to finally launch that first MVP.

59
00:04:11,680 --> 00:04:11,920
>> Yeah.

60
00:04:11,920 --> 00:04:18,639
If you could just give me a breakdown of you know how long this took, how much did you actually spend to get this prototype put together?

61
00:04:18,639 --> 00:04:21,519
What did that look like >> with the student developer?

62
00:04:21,519 --> 00:04:23,759
What I did was I just put in all my savings.

63
00:04:23,759 --> 00:04:28,960
You know, as a non-technical founder, it just took a few months once I actually had the developer.

64
00:04:28,960 --> 00:04:33,600
And that's because all of the content, all of the wireframes before then were already created.

65
00:04:33,600 --> 00:04:37,440
I did want to learn enough to at least be able to communicate what I wanted better.

66
00:04:37,440 --> 00:04:42,400
I just sort of focused a lot on the design, making sure all that was really simple.

67
00:04:42,400 --> 00:04:48,000
The first prototype of Rooted was essentially the panic attack button that would walk you through a panic attack.

68
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:52,400
And that actually hasn't changed a ton over the years because it's really the core of Rooted.

69
00:04:52,400 --> 00:04:54,960
It's the aha moment that really resonates with users.

70
00:04:54,960 --> 00:04:57,520
What's changed is the design and the way it looks right now.

71
00:04:57,520 --> 00:05:03,360
But that core idea of how to stop a panic attack is still there and rooted after all these years.

72
00:05:03,360 --> 00:05:10,320
So I launched with that a simple breathing tool and then the lessons on how to understand panic attacks and anxiety and where they're coming from.

73
00:05:10,320 --> 00:05:10,639
>> All right.

74
00:05:10,639 --> 00:05:13,520
So you launched this, you built this, you're getting early traction.

75
00:05:13,520 --> 00:05:15,680
Now this is a huge app with millions of downloads.

76
00:05:15,680 --> 00:05:17,759
What did that growth timeline look like for you?

77
00:05:17,759 --> 00:05:18,720
How long did it take?

78
00:05:18,720 --> 00:05:20,240
>> So it started off quite slow.

79
00:05:20,240 --> 00:05:24,080
I'd say in the first year we reached around 10,000 downloads.

80
00:05:24,080 --> 00:05:28,560
It wasn't until year two or so that we reached a 100,000 downloads.

81
00:05:28,560 --> 00:05:34,960
And I remember after that, I guess we just knew that there was a real demand for it and kept going.

82
00:05:34,960 --> 00:05:38,880
And I hit a million downloads, I think, in year three.

83
00:05:38,880 --> 00:05:42,400
>> You mentioned just a second ago that you did this with a full-time job.

84
00:05:42,400 --> 00:05:43,520
How did you do that?

85
00:05:43,520 --> 00:05:43,840
>> Yeah.

86
00:05:43,840 --> 00:05:51,360
So when I first started Rooted, I was working 4 days a week and I had told my employers at the time that I was starting Rooted.

87
00:05:51,360 --> 00:05:54,960
I'm doing this like Rooted 3 days a week and this other job 4 days a week.

88
00:05:54,960 --> 00:05:58,880
So I basically had no weekends or social life for quite a few years.

89
00:05:58,880 --> 00:06:00,400
I don't think there's any shortcuts though.

90
00:06:00,400 --> 00:06:02,160
I think that's just something I had to go through.

91
00:06:02,160 --> 00:06:05,039
>> Tell me about that decision to go full-time on Rooted.

92
00:06:05,039 --> 00:06:06,000
What did that look like?

93
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:09,680
>> So I had already been wanting to do it for probably a year before I did it.

94
00:06:09,680 --> 00:06:10,880
Uh revenue was there.

95
00:06:10,880 --> 00:06:13,520
it could sustain me comfortably for over a year.

96
00:06:13,520 --> 00:06:23,120
Yeah, it really happened when there was a lot of shifts at the other job and it just became a lot less enjoyable and I just decided that now is time.

97
00:06:23,120 --> 00:06:28,400
That was about 3 years ago now, so maybe 2 and 1/2 to 3 years into rooted.

