109
00:07:12,319 --> 00:07:16,720
I know that you grew this app from zero to 4 million plus downloads.

110
00:07:16,720 --> 00:07:21,840
What are some of the tactics or maybe the top three things when it comes to growing a mobile or an iPhone app?

111
00:07:21,840 --> 00:07:29,599
First, it was active social media engagement, but I remember that I used to spend literal hours going through posts,

112
00:07:29,599 --> 00:07:35,680
writing helpful comments, leaving links back to Rooted, and really trying to be helpful in what I wrote.

113
00:07:35,680 --> 00:07:38,080
Secondly, I would say press releases.

114
00:07:38,080 --> 00:07:42,080
In the early days, I didn't want to be even known as like the anxiety girl.

115
00:07:42,080 --> 00:07:43,599
I didn't want that to like define me.

116
00:07:43,599 --> 00:07:50,080
Then I realized, you know, once you actually put your name to a story, it does resonate better with the audiences.

117
00:07:50,080 --> 00:07:59,840
I would find people online, journalists that wrote about mental health and then I would read it reach out to them either on LinkedIn or try to get their email and send pitches that way.

118
00:07:59,840 --> 00:08:03,360
It was a ton of work because not many people would ever respond to me.

119
00:08:03,360 --> 00:08:08,800
But what ended up happening is every now and then we'd get featured in a pretty major way for small apps.

120
00:08:08,800 --> 00:08:14,240
So we were in Cosmopolitan, we've been in Women's Health, we were even in Time magazine which was the big one.

121
00:08:14,240 --> 00:08:17,840
All of that really happened from these organic cold emails.

122
00:08:17,840 --> 00:08:21,360
And then the third thing would be a huge focus on app store optimization.

123
00:08:21,360 --> 00:08:27,680
So I focused a lot on making sure that the product matches what the users are looking for.

124
00:08:27,680 --> 00:08:29,280
They see on your product page.

125
00:08:29,280 --> 00:08:35,279
They download the app, they use it, and then they use the same keywords to describe their experience via the user reviews.

126
00:08:35,279 --> 00:08:37,120
That was like the holy circle.

127
00:08:37,120 --> 00:08:42,640
And if you can get that loop going, it I think it's a really strong presence for app store optimization.

128
00:08:42,640 --> 00:08:43,120
>> That's great.

129
00:08:43,120 --> 00:08:47,600
And would you have any advice for how to be helpful in 2025?

130
00:08:47,600 --> 00:08:50,320
You probably talked to a lot of people that are just starting to build apps.

131
00:08:50,320 --> 00:08:53,519
What's your advice on being helpful and doing something similar to what you did?

132
00:08:53,519 --> 00:08:57,200
>> I'd say not leading with, hey, this is my app.

133
00:08:57,200 --> 00:09:04,000
Go download it, but actually maybe even answering something like a question online that your app answers.

134
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:06,640
I would almost take something like from a rooted lesson.

135
00:09:06,640 --> 00:09:13,360
So, let's say there's somebody makes a post saying that, you know, they had this like horrible experience with anxiety on a run today.

136
00:09:13,360 --> 00:09:16,480
Then I could like kind of share like why that might have happened and why, you know,

137
00:09:16,480 --> 00:09:17,120
it's normal.

138
00:09:17,120 --> 00:09:18,399
it's okay and whatnot.

139
00:09:18,399 --> 00:09:18,720
>> Okay.

140
00:09:18,720 --> 00:09:23,040
So, beyond the tactics which we talked a little bit about, I want to know now, you know,

141
00:09:23,040 --> 00:09:24,480
what's the bigger strategy?

142
00:09:24,480 --> 00:09:27,680
What does it take to build a successful app in 2025?

143
00:09:27,680 --> 00:09:31,360
What would be your playbook that you'd give to someone who is just starting out today?

144
00:09:31,360 --> 00:09:31,680
>> Right.

145
00:09:31,680 --> 00:09:36,320
So, step one, build a product that actually delivers what your page promises.

146
00:09:36,320 --> 00:09:42,160
That'll lead not only to more positive downloads, aka like people leaving positive experiences,

147
00:09:42,160 --> 00:09:43,920
but people will also then share it.

148
00:09:43,920 --> 00:09:47,040
and like the word of mouth engagement is quite important.

149
00:09:47,040 --> 00:09:49,200
Step two, listen to your users.

150
00:09:49,200 --> 00:09:51,279
So user reviews are super important.

151
00:09:51,279 --> 00:10:00,880
Oftentimes everything you need to know is written in the user reviews and sometimes your own assumption of what a user needs might not actually be what they do need.

152
00:10:00,880 --> 00:10:04,480
Step three, optimize app store presence continuously.

153
00:10:04,480 --> 00:10:08,640
Doing a release frequently shows that you continue to work on the app.

154
00:10:08,640 --> 00:10:13,600
I do one once every week and that shows that you're constantly working on fixing bugs,

155
00:10:13,600 --> 00:10:15,600
improving the user experience.

156
00:10:15,600 --> 00:10:18,079
And step four, partner strategically.

157
00:10:18,079 --> 00:10:28,959
So be that a wellness organization, um we've done a few B2B contracts as well, a ton of different therapy groups and psychologist offices are recommending and using Rooted and

158
00:10:28,959 --> 00:10:32,160
this has been something that's been helpful now in 2025.

159
00:10:32,160 --> 00:10:37,920
One thing that I'm curious about as someone who's built a really successful app, also helped a lot of people build successful apps.

160
00:10:37,920 --> 00:10:40,880
What is like the most important metrics to be tracking?

161
00:10:40,880 --> 00:10:42,480
Is it revenue downloads?

162
00:10:42,480 --> 00:10:43,279
What is it?

163
00:10:43,279 --> 00:10:48,079
>> Well, for me, and I think especially being in the mental health space, it's been about user reviews.

164
00:10:48,079 --> 00:10:51,839
So, our rating, we've been able to maintain a 4.8 out of five rating.

165
00:10:51,839 --> 00:10:54,480
And this is really, really important to me.

166
00:10:54,480 --> 00:10:59,680
users leave comments about how Rooted has helped them go back to work, go back to school,

167
00:10:59,680 --> 00:11:01,920
and just reclaim confidence in their lives.

168
00:11:01,920 --> 00:11:11,680
We've also realized that based on usage that we're able to now take a panic attack and users are feeling better from the panic attack within under 2 minutes.

169
00:11:11,680 --> 00:11:18,560
It's just been really exciting to to work on that and kind of see really how effective Rooted is and what users say about it.

170
00:11:18,560 --> 00:11:28,240
I think actually our focus on tracking user reviews and the quality of rooted over revenue has been a big factor as to why we've grown.

171
00:11:28,240 --> 00:11:31,600
>> All right, so we talked all about how you built this app, how you came up with the idea,

172
00:11:31,600 --> 00:11:34,720
how you grew it to millions of users.

173
00:11:34,720 --> 00:11:35,839
Can we see the app?

174
00:11:35,839 --> 00:11:37,040
How does it actually work?

175
00:11:37,040 --> 00:11:37,279
>> Yeah.

176
00:11:37,279 --> 00:11:41,760
So, when you first open the app, you're greeted with this blue app mascot named Ron.

177
00:11:41,760 --> 00:11:46,560
The main feature here is if you're in the middle of a panic attack, you'll see this red button.

178
00:11:46,560 --> 00:11:48,000
This is an SOS button.

179
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:55,200
And it'll basically ask you how you're feeling based on either wanting to feel okay in the moment or wanting to face the panic attack head-on.

180
00:11:55,200 --> 00:12:00,720
And it walks you through these prompts which help to essentially activate the parasympathetic nervous system.

181
00:12:00,720 --> 00:12:03,680
And the parasympathetic nervous system is the one that calms us down.

182
00:12:03,680 --> 00:12:05,839
There's also this tool for deep breathing.

183
00:12:05,839 --> 00:12:08,880
And probably my favorite features are these lessons.

184
00:12:08,880 --> 00:12:13,120
They're actually lessons on understanding anxiety, what the physical mental effects are,

185
00:12:13,120 --> 00:12:15,279
the causes and theories and so forth.

186
00:12:15,279 --> 00:12:21,760
We also have a journal tool where you can kind of share what your feelings are, share what you've accomplished,

187
00:12:21,760 --> 00:12:24,320
what's weighing you down, what you're grateful for.

188
00:12:24,320 --> 00:12:29,120
We also have over 100 visualizations and sleep sounds.

189
00:12:29,120 --> 00:12:32,320
And then most recently, we have a games tool.

190
00:12:32,320 --> 00:12:35,680
And these are supposed to be really simple, relaxing games.

191
00:12:35,680 --> 00:12:38,880
Users have asked for this for many years.

192
00:12:38,880 --> 00:12:46,880
So the idea is for the games to be really simple things that you can play when you are on a plane or in a busy subway.

193
00:12:46,880 --> 00:12:51,680
Just things to kind of distract you when you're feeling a little anxious in the moment.

194
00:12:51,680 --> 00:12:59,519
Now that we have as many downloads as we have, whenever I launch something, I almost instantly like within a week I get to see thousands of people use it,

195
00:12:59,519 --> 00:12:59,839
right?

196
00:12:59,839 --> 00:13:01,760
So that's just been incredible.

197
00:13:01,760 --> 00:13:02,000
>> All right.

198
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:03,360
Well, thank you for showing me that.

199
00:13:03,360 --> 00:13:08,399
I think what you built is awesome and it's an amazing tool for millions of people to use.

200
00:13:08,399 --> 00:13:08,959
You've done it.

201
00:13:08,959 --> 00:13:09,839
You built an app.

202
00:13:09,839 --> 00:13:10,959
It's really successful.

203
00:13:10,959 --> 00:13:12,160
You quit your full-time job.

204
00:13:12,160 --> 00:13:13,360
You do this for a living now.

205
00:13:13,360 --> 00:13:20,000
Uh what would be your advice to someone who's maybe just starting out, maybe they've just started building an app or they have an idea for an app.

206
00:13:20,000 --> 00:13:22,560
What would be your advice to someone who's starting out?

207
00:13:22,560 --> 00:13:26,240
>> I would suggest that you listen to users very closely.

208
00:13:26,240 --> 00:13:28,639
They will have the answers you need.

209
00:13:28,639 --> 00:13:30,480
They'll help you know what to focus on.

210
00:13:30,480 --> 00:13:34,880
And I believe, especially in the mental health space, at the end of the day, that's who we're most responsible.

211
00:13:34,880 --> 00:13:37,920
Launching Rooted with the MVP and getting that original feedback.

212
00:13:37,920 --> 00:13:43,360
I mean, to this day, I still read all the user reviews, even though I have somebody else do the responses now.

213
00:13:43,360 --> 00:13:48,079
I still go in and I make sure I know what's going on and just to have a pulse on what users are saying.

214
00:13:48,079 --> 00:13:51,200
I'd also recommend taking care of yourself along the way.

215
00:13:51,200 --> 00:13:55,040
I think there were definitely quite a few points where I almost reached burnout.

